   La Jolla Bancorp's
   Holders Back Merger
   With Security Pacific
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   SPC LJC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN DIEGO -- La Jolla Bancorp said shareholders approved
its agreement to merge with Security Pacific Corp. in an
exchange of stock valued at about $110 million.
   La Jolla said 64% of its shareholders approved the merger
at the company's annual meeting on Friday, while fewer than
2% voted against it. The agreement calls for the conversion,
at a rate to be determined later, of each of La Jolla
Bancorp's about seven million shares outstanding into the
right to receive about $15 in market value of Security
Pacific common stock.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday,
Security Pacific's stock closed unchanged at $38.50 a share.
La Jolla Bancorp's stock closed at $13.875 a share, down 12.5
cents, in American Stock Exchange trading.
   Security Pacific is a Los Angeles-based bank holding
company. La Jolla Bank &amp; Trust Co., La Jolla Bancorp's
principal unit, has 12 branches in San Diego.
   The two companies signed a letter of intent to merge last
October and ratified a definitive merger pact in December. La
Jolla Bancorp said it expects federal regulators to approve
the combination in the next two months.
