<HL>
   Dallas Semiconductor,
   SGS-Thomson Settle,
   Enter Patent Accord
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   DS TCSFY
</CO>
<IN>
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Dallas Semiconductor Corp. said that all
lawsuits between it and SGS Thomson Microelectronics Inc.
have been settled and that the two companies have entered
into a comprehensive, patent cross-licensing agreement.
   Dallas Semiconductor, a specialty chip maker whose
personnel include several former employees of SGS-Thomson's
predecessor, sued SGS-Thomson in state court in January over
a 1986 agreement to swap proprietary information. SGS-Thomson
responded with a suit in federal court, charging patent
infringement.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under terms of the patent cross-licensing agreement,
confirmed by SGS-Thomson, all state court litigation has been
dismissed, and a consent judgment has been entered in federal
court.
   Dallas Semiconductor said the cross-licensing agreement
covers virtually every patent owned by both companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
