<HL>
   Two Banks Seem
   To Hold Fate
   Of Trump Loan
   ----
   By Neil Barsky
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   DRSDY F.SGF BT CCI CMB MHC FFB MIDL NW
</CO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Donald Trump's pending $65 million bank loan appears to be
in the hands of two foreign banks who, as of yesterday, still
hadn't agreed to the proposal.
   Negotiations with the banks, West German-based Dresdner
Bank and French-based Societe General, are expected to resume
today, as Mr. Trump's creditors race to complete the proposal
by tomorrow night's deadline. If Mr. Trump doesn't receive
the $65 million by then, he will likely default on bond
payments on Trump's Castle, which could trigger other
defaults on his $2 billion in bank debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   All told, 70 lending institutions must agree to the plan
that would allow Mr. Trump to suspend interest payments on
some $800 million of the bank debt. While a vast majority of
the banks have agreed to the proposal, a single dissent would
wreck the deal, bankers say.
   The $65 million loan would be supplied by Mr. Trump's
major creditors: units of Bankers Trust Corp., Citicorp,
Chase Manhattan Corp., First Fidelity Bancorp, Manufacturers
Hanover Corp., Midlantic and the U.S. unit of National
Westminster Bank PLC.
   On Friday, three Japanese banks that, like Dresdner, hold
first mortgages on the Trump Tower in Manhattan, lifted their
opposition to the bailout plan. Those banks have purchased
pieces of an original $75 million loan issued to Mr. Trump by
Chase Manhattan.
   The overwhelming majority of the 54 participants in more
than $1 billion in loans issued by Citicorp have also agreed
to the proposal, though a few holdouts remain, according to
people close to the negotiations.
   After a long silence, Mr. Trump issued a statement Friday
that expressed optimism that the deal would get done. "An
overwhelming number of the participating lenders,
representing both national and international financial
institutions, have now joined the major banks in supporting
our plan," the statement said.
   On Saturday, attorneys representing Chase Manhattan met
with representatives from Dresdner to get the German bank to
accept a second mortgage on the property, to no avail. Today,
senior executives from Chase are expected to call on Dresdner
officers to lobby for the proposal. Societe General owns less
than $15 million of a $200 million loan Chase issued to Mr.
Trump for his purchase of a 72-acre vacant site on
Manhattan's Upper West Side, according to an individual close
to the talks.
   The plan's purpose, say bankers, is to help Mr. Trump
avoid bankruptcy court. Instead, the banks want to have an
orderly sale of assets, and to give Mr. Trump time to improve
operations in his airline, casino and hotels empire.
   Lawyers for the banks worked through the weekend, while
many of the bankers took yesterday off. If the deal is agreed
to by tomorrow, the seven banks have arranged for a bridge
loan to be extended in case the paperwork for the $65 million
loan can't be completed in time, said a person close to the
talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900625-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900625-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Henley Group Inc.
   Seeks to Dispose
   Of Itel Shares
   ----
   By Robert L. Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   HENG ITL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Henley Group Inc., moving forward in its plan to
liquidate, said it intends to dispose of as much as its
entire 38.5% stake in Itel Corp., a chunk of shares valued at
$381 million at current prices.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Henley said it plans to sell eight million to 16.7 million of
its 18.7 million common shares in the Chicago-based leasing
concern through a public offering "or otherwise."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Henley spokesman, Norman Ritter, said the filing
includes the possibility that some of the Itel shares would
be swapped with current Henley holders for their Henley
shares. But at least some of the Itel stake will be sold, Mr.
Ritter said.
   Henley, based in Hampton, N.H., said it plans to
contribute the remaining two million shares to Fisher
International Inc., a Henley subsidiary that Henley plans to
spin off.
   Henley acquired the Itel shares in 1988 as part of a $1.2
billion cash and stock payment from Itel. In return, Henley
sold Itel its stake in Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. and
leasing operations, among other holdings.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday, Itel
shares fell 37.5 cents, to $20.375. Henley stock fell 25
cents to $31 a share in national over-the-counter trading.
   Itel officials couldn't be reached for comment, but
Henley's holdings weren't considered a threat to Itel. The
1988 transaction included a 10-year standstill agreement that
restricted how Henley could vote or trade its Itel stake.
   At the time, Itel Chairman Samuel Zell asserted in an
interview that the terms of the standstill agreement meant
that Henley would be distributing its Itel shares to Henley
shareholders. But a Henley spokesman said at the time that
Henley planned to keep its Itel shares.
   Henley's disposition of Itel shares fits with its current
plan to liquidate. Henley has said it intends to spin off its
Fisher Scientific Group unit and 35% of Pneumo Abex Corp. The
spinoff plan is being reviewed by the SEC.
   Proceeds from the sale of any of the rest of the 16.7
million shares will be used to reduce Henley's huge debt load
of about $1.5 billion, a Henley spokesman said. Most of that
debt, about $1.03 billion, is Pneumo Abex's.
   But Henley said its plans don't currently call for using
proceeds of the sale to lighten that load before the 35%
spinoff. At current market prices, the 16.7 million Itel
shares are valued at $340.3 million.
   In addition to its railcar and container leasing
operations, Itel is involved in dredging, distribution and
wire making. It also invests in stocks of other companies.
</TEXT>
