<HL>
   Enterprise:
   Militant Small-Business Coalition is Fighting City Hall
   ---
   Tucson, Ariz., Entrepreneurs Protest
   Government Policies, Tight Credit
   ----
   By John R. Emshwiller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<LP>
   In most struggling regions, scared and angry entrepreneurs
voice their frustrations mainly to each other. But in Tucson,
Ariz., they are marching on city hall.
   Angry at the effects of a credit crunch, regional economic
slowdown and government policies, Tucson entrepreneurs
organized the Tucson Business Coalition last February to
fight back. Leaders of the grass-roots organization say
membership is already at 1,400 and still growing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In April, the coalition organized a protest march to a
city council meeting by several hundred business people, who
wore buttons and carried banners and signs in the coalition's
colors of red and black. The black, says an organizer, is to
mourn the businesses that have died while red is for the ones
still alive but bleeding.
   Being law-abiding citizens, marchers were careful to stay
on the sidewalk and cross with the lights, organizers add.
Confronted with a mass of angry business owners, the council
moved to the nearby convention center to hear them out. A
similar march was held the next day to Pima County's board of
supervisors meeting.
   "We haven't had much help from the big boys. So we are
going to do some things on our own," says Byron Howard,
coalition co-chairman and owner of B&amp;H Properties, a local
land-developer.
   Similar groups are forming in other Arizona cities, say
coalition leaders, and the protest may eventually go
nationwide. "We would like to take this movement right into
Washington, D.C.," says Bruce Greer, the coalition's other
co-chairman and owner of Bruce Greer Construction Inc.
   Some observers believe the ground is getting more fertile
for such militancy. "There is a rising anger among
small-business people" over government-imposed costs and
tight credit, says John Galles, executive vice president of
National Small Business United, a 67,000-member advocacy
group based in Washington, D.C.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher earlier this month
said a "serious" credit crunch is beginning to grip small
business and other sections of the economy.
   However, Tucson coalition leaders are finding their
message isn't universally welcomed. For instance, Mr. Greer
says some of his construction equipment was recently
vandalized. He says the grafitti on the machines indicated it
was done by people who objected to some of his
pro-development stands on behalf of the coalition.
   The coalition aims to prune the size and cost of
government and get it out of competition with private
enterprise. It also hopes to lessen the dependence of small
businesses on big financial institutions; coalition members
assert the institutions have turned their backs on lending to
small businesses. Local bankers reply that they are still
interested in lending to small businesses but say the slowing
economic growth rate has hurt the ability of many firms to
qualify for loans.
   Dozens of coalition members are spending evenings and
weekends combing through city and county budgets looking for
spending for the governments to slash. The coalition is even
trying to set up an alternate banking arrangement for members
through a local credit union.
   Tucson Mayor Thomas Volgy decries some of the group's
"slash-and-burn" tactics, but says it is emerging as a force
to be reckoned with. Mr. Volgy says the coalition's rise
helped kill a recent move to increase business licensing
fees. Because of the coalition, "government is much more
sensitive on a day-to-day basis to the needs of small
business," he says.
   Tucson's business problems can be traced to the boom times
of the mid-1980's when Arizona was one of the U.S.'s
fastestgrowing states. Then, the biggest credit problem was
finding ways to spend the multimillion-dollar loans that
banks and thrifts were spewing out.
   All that easy money led to some business binges,
especially in real estate. Now Tucson is feeling the
hangover. While population and income levels are still
growing at about 2% a year, that's only a third of the rate
of the mid-1980's. Since most businesses had geared up for
the faster growth, the slowing "feels like a recession," says
Marshall Vest, an economist at the University of Arizona.
Bankruptcy filings in metropolitan Tucson last year hit a
record 3,700 and in the first quarter of this year were up
another 27%, he says.
   Exacerbating the slower pace, most of the state's major
savings and loans have been taken over by the federal
government and have adopted lending procedures that make
Uncle Sam look like Uncle Scrooge. Tucson residents joke that
the government has taken the "L" out of their S&amp;L's.
   While commercial banks are in better shape, they also have
turned more cautious, Tucson business people and economists
say. Georgia Carlson and her husband, Glenn, recently
discovered just how cautious when their bank told them it was
calling in the $500,000 credit line on their two businesses,
which supply various items to the construction industry.
   Mrs. Carlson says the businesses have never missed a
payment on the credit line. But both were hard hit by the
construction downturn, and the Carlsons' banker told them
their firms "had become bad risks," Mrs. Carlson recalls. She
says that unless they can come up with some way to pay off
the outstanding bank balance, they face bankruptcy and
possible loss of their home. (The credit line was personally
guaranteed.) "I'm damn mad and I'm not going to take this,"
says Mrs. Carlson, a leader in the business coalition.
   Such anger was a driving force behind the coalition's
formation. But the specific catalyst came from a local
talk-radio show that began airing small-business owners'
complaints. Then the station, KTUC, decided to hold a
luncheon earlier this year where business people could give
local politicians a piece of their mind. "People told me we
would be lucky to get a couple of dozen people there,"
recalls Tom Hassey, KTUC's owner.
   Some 500 showed up, along with most major local
politicians. Attendees say the business people ran out of
time before they ran out of gripes. For instance, Nicholas
Locastro, a restaurant owner and coalition activist, says his
property taxes more than doubled since 1983 and his liquor
license fees went up 50% in the past two years.
   Given the outpouring, some entrepreneurs decided an
organization was needed. "Instead of just lone whining
businessmen, we thought we'd at least have a bunch of whining
businessmen," jokes Jim Hilkemeyer, who operates two fitness
centers.
   Membership in the coalition is restricted to locally owned
small businesses, says Mr. Howard, the co-chairman. "We
aren't the chamber of commerce or old guard," he says with
some disdain. "We want people who know what it is like to
have a Friday morning with a $150,000 payroll due and only
$30,000 in the bank."
   Entree costs $25 and as much free time as an entrepreneur
can devote. Hundreds of volunteer hours are being put into
searching for ways to cut government budgets, merge
departments and privatize such activities as printing and
street construction. Mayor Volgy says the coalition's efforts
have led to a "department-by-department examination of what
is and isn't being contracted out."
   Coalition leaders say they aren't sure how much lasting
change all this activity will produce. But it has already led
some business people to do things they wouldn't have dreamed
of a year ago.
   Bob Jones, president and part owner of Apache Business
Systems Inc., says he always disdained protest marches and
made fun of participants. But when the coalition marched on
city hall, he was among the protesters. "I put my dignity
aside. We had to get {people's} attention," he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900625-0078
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900625-0078.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law -- Legal Beat:
   Lisa Jones, Convicted Ex-Assistant
   At Drexel, Gets 10 Months in Jail
   ----
   By Ann Hagedorn and Laurie P. Cohen
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN AXP TWX MOB
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Lisa Jones, a former trader's assistant at Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. who was convicted of perjury last year, was
resentenced to 10 months in prison.
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand, prompted
by a recent decision from the Second U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, reduced Ms. Jones's prison term from 18 to 10
months. The judge also cut Ms. Jones's financial penalty from
$50,000 to about $40,000.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The 27-year old Ms. Jones, a former runaway who made
$100,000 a year at the now collapsed Drexel, sobbed as Judge
Sand announced his decision. Her attorney, Daniel Bookin, had
urged the judge to reduce her punishment to probation. He
expressed his concern that her fragile mental condition would
be further damaged by a stay in prison.
   Mr. Bookin read from a letter his client had sent Judge
Sand in which she described "never-ending sleepness nights
and days filled with anxiety." He also stressed that Ms.
Jones's sentence was unduly harsh in comparison with those of
more powerful players convicted during the government's
crackdown on insider trading on Wall Street.
   Ms. Jones was convicted of five counts of perjury and two
counts of obstruction of justice for lying to a grand jury
looking into allegedly illegal trading involving Drexel. Her
trial drew considerable attention because she had worked for
former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg, who was later
convicted along with five partners of now-defunct
Princeton/Newport L.P. for engaging in a scheme with Drexel
aimed at generating bogus tax losses. Her attorney depicted
her as a hapless pawn in the government's sweeping
investigation.
   Mr. Bookin, of the San Francisco law firm Farella Braun &amp;
Martel, appealed the conviction and the original 18-month
sentence on the basis of alleged conflicts of interest by her
trial lawyer who also represented other Drexel employees. The
court upheld the conviction. But it ruled that Judge Sand had
improperly increased Ms. Jones's sentence beyond the level
deemed appropriate under the federal sentencing guidelines.
   The government sought a steep penalty based on the
argument that Ms. Jones's perjury had cost the government
time and money in its effort to prove its case against
Princeton/Newport. The appeals panel, seeing no evidence of
such cost, asked the judge to resentence Ms. Jones.
   At Friday's hearing, prosecutor Neil Cartusciello stressed
that Ms. Jones "could have added very relevant evidence" to
the Princeton/Newport investigation. After her conviction,
according to individuals familiar with the case, the
government urged Ms. Jones to cooperate in their probes, but
she declined. Mr. Cartusciello told the judge that Ms. Jones
"still has information concealed."
   ---
   FORMER HOLLY FARMS CEO sues Wachtell Lipton.
   The former president and chief executive officer of Holly
Farms Corp. sued Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &amp; Katz, alleging
that an error by the New York law firm cost him and other
employees of the poultry and feed-products concern millions
of dollars.
   In a suit filed earlier this month in Memphis, Tenn.,
Chancery Court, R. Lee Taylor II alleged that Wachtell failed
to "exercise due skill, care and diligence in connection with
rendering advice" to Holly and its former board. Mr. Taylor
has charged that Wachtell made an error in an amendment it
drafted for Holly's stock bonus plan in January 1989.
   The former Holly executive is suing Wachtell on behalf of
himself and some 600 participants in Holly's stock bonus
plan. Mr. Taylor had previously sued Holly in connection with
the alleged error. The litigation is pending.
   Mr. Taylor is seeking a jury trial and unspecified
damages. While the suit doesn't state how much money the
drafting error cost employees, attorneys familiar with the
matter had previously estimated the cost at more than $35
million.
   In recent years, state courts have increasingly ruled that
if lawyers act negligently, they may be liable to third
parties.
   Wachtell declined to comment on the suit. But in a court
filing opposing Mr. Taylor's action against Wachtell, lawyers
representing the New York firm say that Mr. Taylor, in his
capacity as a director and chief executive of Holly, "had
direct responsibility to supervise and control the review and
approval of the stock bonus plan." They say that Wachtell
could also sue Mr. Taylor for contributory negligence in
connection with the plan.
   Mr. Taylor was fired from his job last August, less than
two months after Tyson Foods Inc., another poultry producer,
acquired Holly for about $1.29 billion.
   Tyson's purchase ended eight months of bidding and
litigation with Holly.
   ---
   INS LIST bars 340,000 aliens from entering U.S. for
political reasons.
   According to the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, which
obtained an edited version of the "Lookout" list from the
Immigration and Naturalization Service under a court order,
the number of people listed is far greater than many people
have estimated. The list dates back to 1904, but two-thirds
of the entries were made since 1980.
   "This is the first time we've gotten a sense of the
magnitude," said Arthur Helton an attorney with the
human-rights group. The 370-page document lists the dates
that individuals were added to the list and is broken down by
country. A federal judge previously ruled that for privacy
reasons, the individuals' names couldn't be disclosed. The
committee plans to ask U.S. Judge Leonard Sand in federal
court in Manhattan to order the INS to divulge further
details, such as the individuals' professions.
   The list is mainly used to identify non-Americans who fall
under three sweeping political categories under the 1952
McCarran-Walter Act. Under that law, people can be prohibited
from entering the U.S. if they are considered a threat to the
"public interest," a threat to "national security," or
affiliated with any Communist or totalitarian party. Nearly
all the individuals listed were listed under the third
category.
   In the first three months of this year, 4,399 people were
added to the list, including 401 from China and 3,486 from
Eastern Europe.
   The list includes people from 146 different countries and
other jurisdictions, such as Palestine and Hong Kong. China
accounts for the largest number of entries on the list,
106,777; second is the Soviet Union, 33,064; third is
Yugoslavia, 31,734; fourth is Hungary, 28,450; and fifth is
Poland, 24,608. Mexico ranked 10th, with 5,402, and Japan
ranked 11th with 4,393.
   It is unclear whether some people were listed more than
once over the years, so the exact number of individuals can't
be determined. Often individuals don't learn that they are on
the list until they apply for a visa or until they arrive in
the U.S. A spokesman for the INS couldn't be reached for
comment.
   Mr. Helton said he thinks the committee's findings will
spur legislators to change the law. "I think they will be
stunned by the magnitude of the lookout list and its recent
escalation," he said.
   ---
   AMERICAN EXPRESS TESTS prepaid legal services for
cardholders.
   The prepaid legal services of Signature Group of
Schaumburg, Ill., are being offered to about one percent of
American Express Co.'s 25.6 million U.S. cardholders.
   The solicitation is the financial-services company's first
test of whether cardholders are interested in paying monthly
fees to be eligible for fixed-price legal services. Signature
Group is a unit of Montgomery Ward &amp; Co., which is a
subsidiary of Mobil Corp.
   For $6.75 a month, cardholders will be able to retain an
attorney to handle an uncontested divorce for $210, a will
and a minor's trust for $170 or a noncommercial real estate
closing for $185, as well as other services.
   Maureen Bailey, a spokeswoman for American Express, says
that if a second solicitation proves successful, the company
may expand the service to all cardholders by the end of the
year.
   ---
   KAYE SCHOLER WILL MERGE with a bankruptcy law firm.
   Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays &amp; Handler, a 355-lawyer New
York law firm, approved a proposal to merge with the
14-lawyer Levin &amp; Weintraub, Crames &amp; Edelman, also in New
York. All five Levin &amp; Weintraub partners will become
partners at Kaye Scholer. The merger will become effective
July 1.
   Levin &amp; Weintraub, one of the nation's best-known
bankruptcy law firms, primarily represents debtors, including
Revco D.S. Inc. and Manville Corp.
   Kaye Scholer's bankruptcy lawyers represent mostly
creditors, including Equitable Life Assurance Society of the
U.S.
   ---
   HBO IS ACCUSED of violating song copyrights.
   In a trial that began this week in Manhattan, Broadcast
Music Inc., a not-for-profit group that represents thousands
of composers, claims that Home Box Office is transmitting
movies and programs that use BMI-licensed songs without
permission.
   BMI has asked U.S. District Judge John Sprizzo to issue an
injunction barring HBO, a Time Warner Inc. subsidiary, from
broadcasting the programming unless it pays licensing fees
for the songs. BMI also asked the judge to rule that it can
require separate licensing agreements from national cable
programmers, such as HBO, and from the programmers' local
cable-system customers.
   HBO maintains that it has an oral agreement with BMI
allowing it to transmit movies using the songs. The company
has also charged that BMI is a monopoly and that the group
has taken steps to make it more difficult for the cable
industry to license its music.
   ---
   Wade Lambert and Arthur S. Hayes contributed to this
article.
