<HL>
   Panel Calls for Sharp Cut
   In Worker Radiation Limit
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- An international commission recommended
sharply lower radiation exposure limits for workers regularly
exposed to high levels of radiation.
   The International Commission on Radiological Radiation
Protection, which conducts research into the effects of
radiation on humans, said the risks from ionizing radiation
are about three times as high as was estimated a decade ago.
The organization, made up of scientists and physicians from
the industrialized countries, recommended lowering the
acceptable level of exposure to two rems a year, measured as
an average over five-year basis, from five rems a year. A rem
is a measure of radiation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which sets standards
for worker exposure levels in the U.S., currently sets a
limit of five rems a year with a maximum exposure of three
rems in any three-month period. An NRC official declined to
comment on the new recommendation pending review of the
commission's report.
   The chairman of the international commission, Dr. Dan
Beninson of Argentina, estimated that 1.5 million people in
the U.S. were involved in occupations that would put them at
risk of exposure beyond the new suggested range. Dr. Beninson
said that people working in occupations such as nuclear plant
repair, medical radiology and uranium mining could be
affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900625-0017
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900625-0017.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Charter Medical Says U.S.
   Is Probing Reimbursements
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   CMDA
</CO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   MACON, Ga. -- Charter Medical Corp. said federal
regulators are investigating the company for possible fraud
related to its Medicare and Medicaid reimbursements.
   C. Michael Ford, chief financial officer of the hospital
and psychiatric-care company, said the Office of the
Inspector General of the Department of Health and Human
Services has interviewed several former reimbursement
specialists from Charter in connection with the probe. The
interviews, he said, have taken place in the past several
months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Ford added, however, that he isn't aware of any
current employees who have been interviewed.
   Mr. Ford said the company expects to make a statement
today regarding the investigation.
   Charter, which went private in a 1988 buy-out, posted a
$67 million loss on revenue of $475.2 million for its second
quarter ended March 31. The year earlier, Charter had a $14.6
million loss on revenue of $397.3 million.
   The most recent figures, which included a $35 million
pretax charge for accounting problems, have raised some
concerns on Wall Street about the company's ability to
service its debt. Charter has said it will cut capital
expenditures and other costs to ensure its ability to meet
its payments.
</TEXT>
