<HL>
   UAL Union Group
   Will Go to Europe
   To Seek Investors
</HL>
<DATE>
06/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR UAL BAB U.RR F.ABI BA GE UTX
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Representatives of the unions seeking to buy
UAL Corp. will travel to Europe this week to talk with
airlines and suppliers about possibly investing in the labor
group's $4.38 billion buy-out proposal.
   Gerald Greenwald, former Chrysler Corp. vice chairman who
is heading the UAL buy-out effort, is expected to talk with
British Airways PLC, Rolls-Royce PLC, a British jet-engine
manufacturer, Airbus Industries, a European aircraft maker
and Guinness Peat Aviation, a leasing company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   British Airways was an investor in a previous, failed
labor-management bid for UAL. In the earlier bid, British
Airways agreed to provide $700 million in equity in return
for a 15% stake in UAL. The airline's management has refused
so far to participate in the new buy-out effort, but
apparently has agreed to listen to a pitch from Mr.
Greenwald, according to an individual familiar with the
situation.
   As previously reported, the unions are also talking with
Boeing Co, the Seattle aircraft manufacturer; General
Electric Co., a Fairfield, Conn., maker of jet engines and
electrical products; and Pratt &amp; Whitney, the jet engine
maker that is a unit of United Technologies Inc., Hartford,
Conn.
   The unions are said to be seeking between $500 million and
$1 billion in financing from these companies that would be
subordinate to any bank financing.
   In return for their investment, the suppliers would
receive either a note or nonvoting stock in UAL as well as
"preferred-supplier" status.
   The labor group is seeking to reduce its dependence on
bank financing. Commercial lenders have been cool to the
transaction, which would result in the largest employee-owned
company in the nation.
   Banks repeatedly have expressed concern about the absence
of an outside equity investor. Currently, the only equity in
the deal is the $2 billion of "sweat equity" the unions
agreed to provide over five years in the form of wage
concessions.
</TEXT>
